+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+
| **INSTRUCTOR ANSWER KEY**                                             |
|                                                                       |
| Module 5 --- SSDLC Mapping Exercise                                   |
|                                                                       |
| *Reveal after groups have presented their answers --- not before*     |
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+

**Stage Key:**

+-------------+-------------+-------------+-------------+-------------+
| **REQ**     | **CODE**    | **SAST**    | **CFG**     | **DAST**    |
|             |             |             |             |             |
| R           | Secure      | Static      | Config &    | DAST & Pen  |
| equirements | Coding      | Analysis    | Secrets     | Test        |
| & Threat    | Standards & | Tools       | Review      |             |
| Modelling   | Review      | (SAST)      |             |             |
+-------------+-------------+-------------+-------------+-------------+

+---+----------+---------------------------------------------------------+
| * | **       | **Reasoning --- Why This Stage? What Would It Have      |
| * | Answer** | Caught?**                                               |
| \ |          |                                                         |
| # |          |                                                         |
| * |          |                                                         |
| * |          |                                                         |
+===+==========+=========================================================+
| * | **CFG**  | The secret key is a hardcoded string literal in source  |
| * |          | code --- present in every git commit from the moment it |
| 1 |          | is written.                                             |
| * |          |                                                         |
| * |          | **How caught:** A secrets scanner (git-secrets,         |
|   |          | truffleHog, gitleaks) flags \"password\" assigned to a  |
|   |          | variable named secret_key. A pre-commit hook catches    |
|   |          | this at push time, before code review begins. Bandit    |
|   |          | (B105) also catches it under SAST.                      |
|   |          |                                                         |
|   |          | **Note:** *CFG and SAST are both valid. CFG is listed   |
|   |          | first because pre-commit secrets scanning runs before   |
|   |          | the SAST pipeline in most modern setups.*               |
+---+----------+---------------------------------------------------------+
| * | **CFG**  | DEBUG=True is a configuration value that belongs in     |
| * |          | environment config, not source code. Its presence in    |
| 2 |          | source means it survives copy-paste to production.      |
| * |          |                                                         |
| * |          | **How caught:** A pre-deployment configuration          |
|   |          | checklist or Bandit (B201 --- flask_debug_true) would   |
|   |          | flag this. The fix --- reading from an environment      |
|   |          | variable --- is a one-line change.                      |
|   |          |                                                         |
|   |          | **Note:** *Either CFG or SAST is defensible. Use the    |
|   |          | disagreement to ask: which gate comes first in          |
|   |          | delegates\' own pipelines?*                             |
+---+----------+---------------------------------------------------------+
| * | **CODE** | MD5 for password hashing has been prohibited by every   |
| * |          | reputable secure coding standard for over a decade.     |
| 3 |          | This is a prohibited-function violation.                |
| * |          |                                                         |
| * |          | **How caught:** A coding standard mandating             |
|   |          | bcrypt/scrypt/Argon2, enforced at PR review, catches    |
|   |          | this before merge. Bandit (B324 --- hashlib) also flags |
|   |          | it.                                                     |
|   |          |                                                         |
|   |          | **Note:** *The flaw lives in the DB seeder, not a live  |
|   |          | route --- reinforcing that security review must cover   |
|   |          | seeding scripts, migration scripts, and test fixtures,  |
|   |          | not just production routes.*                            |
+---+----------+---------------------------------------------------------+
| * | **CODE** | String interpolation inside a SQL call is explicitly    |
| * |          | prohibited by every secure coding standard. A reviewer  |
| 4 |          | who sees an f-string inside db.execute() should reject  |
| * |          | the PR immediately.                                     |
| * |          |                                                         |
|   |          | **How caught:** Code review with a checklist item ---   |
|   |          | \"no string formatting inside SQL calls\" --- catches   |
|   |          | this at PR time. Bandit (B608) also detects it.         |
|   |          | Parameterised queries are the mandated alternative.     |
|   |          |                                                         |
|   |          | **Note:** *SAST catches it too, but code review is the  |
|   |          | earlier human gate. A reviewer would also question why  |
|   |          | raw SQL is used rather than an ORM.*                    |
+---+----------+---------------------------------------------------------+
| * | **DAST** | Storing a username in the session instead of a user_id  |
| * |          | is a design decision with no static code signature.     |
| 5 |          | Detecting it requires runtime reasoning about session   |
| * |          | behaviour.                                              |
| * |          |                                                         |
|   |          | **How caught:** A penetration tester running            |
|   |          | flask-unsign to decode and re-sign the session cookie   |
|   |          | immediately sees the username stored there, and tests   |
|   |          | whether substituting a different username grants        |
|   |          | elevated access.                                        |
|   |          |                                                         |
|   |          | **Note:** *This is the ONLY flaw in the set effectively |
|   |          | invisible to SAST. Use it to establish that pen testing |
|   |          | is irreplaceable --- no automated tool alone catches    |
|   |          | this class of flaw.*                                    |
+---+----------+---------------------------------------------------------+
| * | **REQ**  | The absence of an authentication check is a missing     |
| * |          | design decision, not a coding error. The requirement to |
| 6 |          | protect the route was never written down.               |
| * |          |                                                         |
| * |          | **How caught:** A STRIDE threat model asking \"what if  |
|   |          | an unauthenticated caller requests /profile?\"          |
|   |          | generates the requirement: \"All profile endpoints must |
|   |          | require an authenticated session.\" That requirement    |
|   |          | blocks the route shipping without \@login_required.     |
|   |          |                                                         |
|   |          | **Note:** *SAST and code review cannot reliably detect  |
|   |          | missing authentication --- they cannot know which       |
|   |          | routes require auth unless that is expressed as a       |
|   |          | requirement or policy rule.*                            |
+---+----------+---------------------------------------------------------+
| * | **REQ**  | IDOR is a design flaw. The developer made a deliberate  |
| * |          | choice to accept user_id from the URL. The threat model |
| 7 |          | question --- \"what if the caller supplies a different  |
| * |          | user\'s ID?\" --- was never asked.                      |
| * |          |                                                         |
|   |          | **How caught:** A threat model data flow diagram for    |
|   |          | /profile prompts: \"Where does user_id come from, and   |
|   |          | is the caller authorised to request that ID?\" The      |
|   |          | answer --- URL parameter, no authorisation check ---    |
|   |          | surfaces the flaw before code is written.               |
|   |          |                                                         |
|   |          | **Note:** *Flaws 6 and 7 together show the core value   |
|   |          | of threat modelling: it surfaces authorisation          |
|   |          | requirements that no static or dynamic tool can infer   |
|   |          | from code alone.*                                       |
+---+----------+---------------------------------------------------------+
| * | **SAST** | os.popen() with an f-string argument is a textbook SAST |
| * |          | signature --- unambiguous and direct.                   |
| 8 |          |                                                         |
| * |          | **How caught:** Bandit flags this as B605               |
| * |          | (start_process_with_a_shell) with HIGH severity and     |
|   |          | HIGH confidence on every run. A coding standard         |
|   |          | mandating subprocess.run() with shell=False would also  |
|   |          | catch it at code review.                                |
|   |          |                                                         |
|   |          | **Note:** *Unlike Flaw 5, this has a reliable static    |
|   |          | signature. SAST is the earliest practical gate --- more |
|   |          | consistent than code review for this pattern.*          |
+---+----------+---------------------------------------------------------+

+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+
| **Facilitation Notes --- Expected Disagreements**                     |
|                                                                       |
| -   Flaws 1 & 2: Bandit detects both (B105, B201). CFG vs SAST is a   |
|     valid debate --- ask which gate runs first in delegates\' own     |
|     pipeline.                                                         |
|                                                                       |
| -   Flaws 3 & 4: Developer delegates often assign to SAST. CODE is    |
|     earlier --- PR review happens before the SAST pipeline run in     |
|     most teams. Either is defensible; the earliness principle is the  |
|     key lesson.                                                       |
|                                                                       |
| -   Flaws 6 & 7: Developer delegates frequently assign to Code        |
|     Review. REQ is earlier --- the threat model question (\"what if   |
|     unauthenticated?\") takes 30 seconds vs. hours of review.         |
|     Cheaper-earlier is the key point.                                 |
|                                                                       |
| -   Flaw 5: Surprises most groups. The only flaw SAST cannot reliably |
|     catch. Use it to establish that pen testing is irreplaceable, and |
|     to preview Module 11: without security logging, this attack would |
|     leave no trace.                                                   |
|                                                                       |
| **Key landing point for debrief:** No single gate catches all 8       |
| flaws. REQ catches 2. CODE catches 2. SAST catches 3. CFG catches 2.  |
| DAST catches 1. **You need all five layers.** That is why it is       |
| called a lifecycle, not a checkpoint.                                 |
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+
